<h1>@HI{{tameni}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}}(<em>volitional</em>) <strong>@HI{{tameni}}</strong>, <em>volitional expression</em>
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{no}} <strong>@HI{{tameni}}</strong>
<li> @Ai{{}} <strong>@HI{{tameni}}</strong>
<li> @Ana{{}} <strong>@HI{{tameni}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
This sentence patterns indicates a purpose because the main clause is a volitional expression.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{oneself}}@KJ{{part}}@HI{{no}}@KJ{{store}}@HI{{wo}}@KJ{{hold}}@HI{{tsu}} <strong>@HI{{tameni}}</strong>,
      @KJ{{savings}}@KJ{{gold}}@HI{{shite imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I am saving money in order to have my own shop.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
If the main clause is non-volitional, then <strong>@HI{{tameni}}</strong> is interpreted to mean a reason or cause.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{attend^matter}}no<strong>tameni</strong>@KJ{{what}}mohokano@KJ{{matter}}ga@KJ{{exit^come}}nai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Because of the job I cannot do anything else.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The pattern @N{{}} @HI{{no <strong>tameni</strong>}} can also indicate
"for the benefit of @N{{}}".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{house}}@KJ{{tribe}}@HI{{no}}<strong>@HI{{tameni}}</strong>, @HI{{uchi wo}}@KJ{{build}}@HI{{temasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I will build a house for my family.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The similar expression <a href="grammar-you-ni.html">@HI{{you ni}}</a>
 is used in clauses with verbs that do not contain volition,
whereas <strong>@HI{{tameni}}</strong> is used with verbs that do. Note that if the verb involved
is @HI{{naru}}, then whether or not volition is invovled depends on the sentence.
</p>

